I really like this app.  It's not too much of a hassle to input the information, so it doesn't feel like a chore to use (one of the major problems with budgeting) and it provides enough options to be flexible enough to do just about whatever you want it to do.  You can have a weekly or monthly or annual budget, or even mix them by category (which you can create or delete as needed).  I was reluctant to spend money on it at first, but $6 one-time payment was worth it for such a useful app.  My only gripes are these: 1) The reoccurring expense has an issue where sometimes it can't save a new expense.  I have it frequently, but I can't seem to find the pattern to make it replicable. 2) The budget projections are just totaling up your scheduled income and bills.  This isn't very helpful considering the vast majority of my expenses are things that don't have a fixed monthly price attached such as food, and I don't work a constant set of hours, so I never have any projected income.  I could tell it the average and adjust whenever I get my check but  what I'd really like is a feature which accounts for trends in previous income/expenses, and extrapolates that.

Kudos to the developer of this app - not the huge 'mint' or YNAB or IQ or whatever but I've looked at most of them and after trying, buying in some cases, i've come back to this. Why? Been using on mac 2 yrs and android 3mths no stability problems to date. And guess what: it allows import and really fast allocation into spending areas, full customisation of categories, and its not cloud based which i like a) for security and b) because use is not dependent on connection speed. Its just GREAT and who gives that its UI is not flashy as. Have not had any compatibility issues across platforms. I would encourage this developer to persevere - am guessing its really hard to support multi-platforms if you're not a big player, but this app is a winner. If you want a simple but sophisticated budget planner tracker and tool, get it.

This for me really lets this app down as a useful on-the-move budget logger. It is far more intuitive to see your budget & balance at the point when you input expenses against a particular category ("whoops, only ¬£20 more to spend on food this month") rather than have to first look at one screen then remember a balance, before you go to another screen to input the expenses. replyContent:
The licensing scheme on Android Google Play requires that you are always logged in with your Google 
account on your Android device. If you get this error message, please open Google Play, and make sure 
you are logged in with the account id with which you purchased the app. After this, the app should open fine.

This was the best Financial App I used so far, "Almost Complete".  I should've Rate this 5 Stars if only it was not missing some Accessibility  features (that other Applications have).  First, is to have a Categories on "Income". some of us have a variety of  sources of income which will be comfortable if we can classify and organize  them using Categories.  Second, it needs a more detailed Reports on the "Income" and not only relying on Bar and Pie Charts (and Dates cannot be changed), just like the Reports  on "Expenses", which has Line, Bar and Pie Charts, Tables and the Date  Ranges can be configured.  Third, also it will better to put an "Item" Section just like the "Payee" for those who want to track the Things they are constantly buying or paying, just like on "Payee" which can be used to track People you are paying.  (Other Apps have these features, I know it can be applied)
